RELATIONSHIP BETWEEN ALBEDO AND REFLECTANCE SPECTRA OF ASTEROIDS.  P. K. Hong1, H. Miyamoto1,2,3, T. Niihara1,4, J. M. Dohm1, 1University Museum, University of Tokyo, 7-3-1 Hongo, Bunkyo, Tokyo 113-0033, Japan (hong@um.u-tokyo.ac.jp), 2Department of Earth and Planetary Sciences, University of Tokyo, 7-3-1 Hongo, Bunkyo, Tokyo 113-0033, Japan, 3Planetary Science Institute, 1700 East Fort Lowell, Suite 106, Tucson, AZ 85719-2395, USA, 4Lunar and Planetary Institute, Universities Space Research Association, 3600 Bay Area Boulevard, Houston, TX 77058, USA.   Introduction:  Large amounts of visible and nearinfrared reflectance spectra data of solar system small bodies have been obtained by ground- and space-based telescopic observations and close-up observations by spacecraft in the past few decades. Especially, nearEarth and main-belt asteroids have been observed intensively because of their proximity to Earth. Using the reflectance spectra, and in particular, through a widely recognized classification method based on principal component analysis [1], asteroids have been classified into several types. Despite a sophisticated classification scheme developed thus far, the physical meaning of reflectance spectra is still poorly constrained because of the lack of forward models. There are multiple factors that can influence the spectral signatures. Different types of meteorite samples, for example, can yield a similar shape of reflectance spectra such as black ordinary chondrites and carbonaceous chondrites [2]. The degeneracy of reflectance spectra may suggest that there is an application limit of this classification scheme based solely on reflectance spectra. Our objective is to attempt to extract the physical meaning of reflectance spectra. With the above consideration, here we present our study through comparative analysis of geometric albedo and spectra of a wide range of asteroid types. Though albedo data (especially geometric albedo) have been accumulated as a result of ground- and spacebased observations, their relationship with reflectance spectra are not fully understood. Our results indicate distinct trends among the various asteroid types.  Albedo and Spectrum Data and Methodology:  We compiled visible/infrared reflectance spectra within the region of 0.45 to 2.45 Œºm based on published databases. Most of the spectra that we use are from IRTF Near-IR Spectroscopy of Asteroids [3], which are the result of disk-integrated spectroscopy. We also use spectra of some small bodies explored by spacecraft, including Ida [4], Mathilde [5], Gaspra [6], Steins [7], Toutatis [8], Itokawa [9, 10, 11], Churyumov-Gerasimenko [12], Phobos, and Deimos [13, 14]. All the spectra were sampled with cubic spline fits at a wavelength interval of 0.05 Œºm, resulting in 41 data points. Next, each spectrum was subtracted by its mean. Using the reduced spectrum, we defined the following spectral type index R, which is the difference between correlation coefficients with average S and Ctype spectra as follows: ùëÖ =  ùíï . ùíìc‚Äñùíï‚Äñ‚Äñùíìc‚Äñ‚àí  ùíï . ùíìs‚Äñùíï‚Äñ‚Äñùíìs‚Äñ where t, rc, and rs are the reduced target spectrum, average C-type, and average S-type spectra, respectively. Positive R values more closely approximate Ctype spectra, while negative R values more closely to S-type. We compiled geometric albedo data mostly from Supplemental IRAS Minor Planet Survey [15]. When available, we compiled V-band (~0.55 Œºm) geometric albedo from the literature. Results:  Fig. 1 shows the albedo - spectra comparison for near-Earth and main-belt asteroids. Distinctly, V-type asteroids such as Vesta distribute at the top left, C and D-types at the bottom right, and S-type between V and C-types. More widely distributed are the D and X-types. Phobos, Deimos, and ChuryumovGerasimenko plot with C and D-type. The variance of each cluster appears to increase from top left (V-type) to bottom right (C-type). Discussion:  Our results shown in Fig. 1 indicate that there is a general trend in the distribution of asteroid types, as per the above section. From this study, it appears that geometric albedo plays a significant role in the resulting spectral signature. Thus, our work, shows that there must be more work done to determine the extent that geometric albedo has on the resulting spectral signature, and why there appears to be distinct distributions. While there are many possible factors to influence albedo and reflectance spectrum, we discuss the crystal grain size in the context of thermal histories of asteroids to help explain our results.  Smaller crystal grains generally result in darker reflectance. V-type asteroids are believed to have experienced large-scale melting and differentiation after their accretion as a result of volcanism, as evidenced by the analysis of HED meteorites and by the observation of Vesta by the Dawn spacecraft [16]. Thus the crystal grains would become coarser due to a slow cooling rate, resulting in brighter and more pyroxene-rich surface spectra, which corresponds to the top-left region of Fig. 1. On the other hand, S and C-type would be undifferentiated chondrite asteroids whose peak temperatures after their accretion are relatively low, pre1809.pdf

serving chondrules which generally have finer grain size due to rapid cooling in the presolar nebula. This results in dark featureless surface materials which could correspond to the bottom-right region in Fig. 1, mainly dominated by C-type asteroids. The surface of some C-type asteroids, as exemplified by Ceres and Churyumov-Gerasimenko, could be covered with volatile and organic-rich materials [17]. Such asteroids could accrete beyond the snow line and migrate inward afterwards. This may be the cause of large variance in C-type, especially in terms of albedo, since volatilerich materials are sensitive to a temperature change which alters surface albedo. As evidenced by the analysis of Itokawa samples [18], S-type asteroids have experienced thermal metamorphism after their accretion, causing recrystallization which results in larger crystal grains and in more evident pyroxene signals than C-type.  It is also important to note that although Fig. 1 includes a wide variety of small bodies in terms of its size ranging from hundred meters to hundred kilometers, the general trend still seems to hold. Though preliminary, the albedo-spectra map could be useful for future ground-based observations, since we could derive general nature of asteroids based solely on observable data, similar to Hertzsprung-Russell diagram in astronomy.
